SE3. Simulation in R #1. Suggested Solution

Author

Mykyta Horovoi

Consider the second-order autoregressive process of a general form from the Exercise #1

\[ y_{t} = \delta + \theta_1y_{t-1} + \theta_2y_{t-2} + \varepsilon_{t},\ \varepsilon_{t} \sim iddN(0, \sigma^2)\tag{1} \]

1. Generate a sample of 1000 obs (N = 1000) using the AR(2) process above, assuming \(\varepsilon_{t} \sim iddN(0, \sigma^2)\)

Substitute suggested parameters from the Exercise #1

\[ y_{t} = 2 + 0.3y_{t-1} - 0.6y_{t-2} + \varepsilon_{t}\tag{2} \]

You can simulate \(y_{t}\) using the code below:

# set parameters
delta <- 2 # the constant
theta_1 <- 0.3 # the first coefficient
theta_2 <- -0.6 # the second coefficient
n <- 1002 # the number of observations + 2 initial values

# generate an error term
set.seed(23)
epsilon <- rnorm(n = n, mean = 0, sd = 1)
# create an empty vector with n observations
y <- numeric(n)

# create AR(2) process using the for-loop
for (i in (3:n)) {
  y[i] <- delta + theta_1*y[i-1] + theta_2*y[i-2] + epsilon[i]
}
y <- y[3:n] # drop zero values used for initialization

You can plot the resulting variable to ensure that the simulation is successful:

ggplot(mapping = aes(y = y, x = seq(1, n-2))) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Simulated AR(2) process",
       x = "t",
       y = "*y<sub>t</sub>*") +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_markdown())

2. Get the empirical counterparts of the theoretical ones from the Exercise #1 and compare the results using a table

First, get estimated coefficient \(\hat{\theta_1}\) and \(\hat{\theta_2}\) using the linear regression:
ar2_fit <- lm(y ~ lag(y, 1) + lag(y, 2))
stargazer(ar2_fit, type = "text")

Write down the estimated equation:

\[ \hat{y_{t}} = 1.980 + 0.303\hat{y}_{t-1} - 0.569\hat{y}_{t-2}\tag{3} \] As you can see, coefficients in \((2)\) and \((3)\) are pretty close.

Second, calculate \(E(y_t)\), \(\gamma_0\), \(\gamma_1\), \(\rho_0\), \(\rho_1\), \(\rho_2\), \(\rho_3\), \(\rho_4\), \(\rho_5\).

There are two ways to calculate these values:

  1. manual calculation.

  2. using estimated coefficients \(\hat{\theta_1}\) and \(\hat{\theta_2}\).

1. Manual Calculation

# sample mean
my_mean_manual <- function(y) {
  sum(y)/length(y)
}
mean_y <- my_mean_manual(y)

# sample variance
my_var_manual <- function(y) {
  temp <- (y - my_mean_manual(y))^2
  sum(temp)/(length(temp)-1)
}
var_y <- my_var_manual(y)

# rho_s
# create the general formula for rho of order s
my_rho_manual <- function(y, order) {
  y_bar <- my_mean_manual(y)
  numerator <- sum((y - y_bar) * (lag(y, order)  - y_bar), na.rm = TRUE)
  denominator <- sum((y - y_bar)^2)
  numerator/denominator
}

# rho_1_5
# calculate autocorrelations up to 5th order
rho_vec_manual <- numeric(5)
for (i in 1:length(rho_vec_manual)) {
  rho_vec_manual[i] <- my_rho_manual(y, i)
}

# calculate gamma_1 from rho_1
gamma_1_manual <- rho_vec_manual[1]*var_y

2. Using Estimated Coefficients \(\hat{\theta_1}\) and \(\hat{\theta_2}\)

# get estimated coefficients
theta_1_est <- summary(ar2_fit)$coefficients[2,1]
theta_2_est <- summary(ar2_fit)$coefficients[3,1]

# sample mean and variance estimations are the same

# gamma_1
gamma_1 <- (theta_1_est/(1-theta_2_est))*var_y

# rho_s
# create the general formula for rho of order s using recursion
my_rho <- function(order, theta_1, theta_2) {
  if (order == 0) {
    1
  } else if (order == 1) {
    theta_1/(1-theta_2)
  } else {
    theta_1*my_rho(order - 1, theta_1, theta_2) + theta_2*my_rho(order - 2, theta_1, theta_2)
    }
}
# rho_0
rho_0 <- my_rho(0, theta_1_est, theta_2_est)

# rho_1_5
# calculate autocorrelations up to 5th order
rho_vec <- numeric(5)
for (i in 1:length(rho_vec)) {
  rho_vec[i] <- my_rho(i, theta_1_est, theta_2_est)
}

Notice that resulting parameter values differ slightly between approaches:

Third, calculate theoretical parameters:
# mean
mean_t <- delta/(1 - theta_1 - theta_2)

# rho_1_5
rho_vec_t <- numeric(5)
for (i in 1:length(rho_vec_t)) {
  rho_vec_t[i] <- my_rho(i, theta_1, theta_2)
}

# var
var_y_t <- 1/(1 - theta_1*rho_vec_t[1] - theta_2*rho_vec_t[2])
gamma_1_y_t <- (theta_1/(1 - theta_2))*var_y_t
